Roberto Fonseca - Akokan
2009

Brought to you by TQMP
The Quality Music Project

Best known for his work with the Buena Vista Social Club, where he achieved the seemingly impossible by winning rave reviews when he stepped in after the death of Ruben Gonzales, Roberto Fonseca is one of the most dazzling pianists and accompanists in Cuba. His last solo album continued the Buena Vista links with appearances from Omara Portuondo and the late Cachaito LÃƒâ€˜Ã†â€™pez, but now he has set out to highlight a range of other influences, from Europe to Africa. He starts, once again, with an unaccompanied fragment of a mass, sung by his mother. Then he's away with the virtuoso workout Lo Que Me Hace Vivir, which starts as a lyrical reminder of his gift for melody, then rapidly moves on to stomping R&amp;B and a furious jazz jam. The mood regularly changes, from the lyrical Como En Las Peliculas (an instrumental inspired by films and dedicated to France), to the east European edge of Bulgarian. Then there's a pleasantly drifting song from the Cape Verdean star Mayra Andrade, a far less impressive ballad in English from Venezuela's Raul MidÃƒâ€˜Ã†â€™n, and even a brief vocal from Fonseca himself. A classy set, though he seems to be cramming in as many influences as he can.
-- The Guardian

